  "formatedtext": "Nikon the Dry -  Nikon the Dry  Venerable Nikon the Dry was made a slave by the Polovtsians in the 11th century.  Prior to his capture he had been a monk of the monastery of the Kiev Caves, in what is today Ukraine .  Nikon endured a brutal captivity for a period of more than three years, eventually gaining his freedom by means of a miracle . Venerable Nikon, before his freedom was gained, informed his slave master that Jesus would release him from bondage in three days.  As a consequence his master crippled Nikon's legs so that he could no longer walk.  Nonetheless, three days later Nikon was carried by God to Kiev unseen. Some time later Venerable Nikon's former master encountered the holy man in the city.  The man repented of his former ways, was baptised , and became a disciple of Nikon. Nikon was referred to as \"the Dry\" due to his intense practice of fasting. Venerable Nikon the Dry died in 1101 and is commemorated on the date of his passing to eternity, 11 December, in the Eastern Orthodox and Byzantine Rite Catholic Churches. [1] See also [ edit ] Saints portal Hermit Daniel the Stylite God: Sole Satisfier References [ edit ] ^ https://web.archive.org/web/20071214040547/http://www.westsrbdio.org/prolog/my.html?day=11&month=December Greek Orthodox Calendar Russian Orthodox Calendar This article about a saint is a stub . You can help  by expanding it . v t e This biographical article about a Ukrainian religious figure is a stub . You can help  by expanding it . v t e Retrieved from \" https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Nikon_the_Dry&oldid=951790792 \" Categories : Hermits 1101 deaths Russian saints of the Eastern Orthodox Church Eastern Catholic saints Monks of Kiev Pechersk Lavra Saint stubs European religious biography stubs Ukrainian people stubs Hidden categories: Year of birth unknown All stub articles Navigation menu Personal tools Not logged in Talk Contributions Create account Log in Namespaces Article Talk Variants Views R